1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:05,960
90% of traders fail because they can't 
read Fibonacci signals correctly. 

2
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:13,200
Today it’s time to finally discover how to use 
Fibonacci effectively, in any market condition.
 
  

3
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:16,840
Fibonacci’s effectiveness 
depends on how you apply them. 

4
00:00:16,840 --> 00:00:20,640
And the key is to use them on 
the correct price swings. 
  

5
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:24,800
When you're looking at a price 
chart, you'll see many price swings. 

6
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:29,320
You might connect two points on the 
chart that seem significant to you,  

7
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:33,200
but another trader might choose different points. 

8
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:39,560
This doesn't mean one of you is wrong; it just 
highlights the subjective nature of this tool.
  

9
00:00:39,560 --> 00:00:45,720
To apply Fibonacci retracements correctly, you 
need to start by determining the dominant trend. 

10
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:51,240
Once you've identified the trend, your 
next step is to find the most obvious swing  

11
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:57,720
high and swing low. These are the points 
you'll use to draw your Fibonacci lines.
  

12
00:00:57,720 --> 00:01:04,120
In a bullish trend, you'll draw the Fibonacci 
retracement from the swing low to the swing high. 

13
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:09,720
This makes sense because in an uptrend, you're 
looking for potential support levels, where the  

14
00:01:09,720 --> 00:01:16,360
price might pause or reverse during a pullback. 
 
In a bearish trend, you'll draw from the  

15
00:01:16,360 --> 00:01:20,400
swing high to the swing low.
You're looking for potential  

16
00:01:20,400 --> 00:01:26,160
resistance levels, where the price 
might stall or reverse during a bounce.
  

17
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:31,040
When drawing these lines, it's important 
to use the wicks of the candlesticks for  

18
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:35,800
your swings, not just the bodies.
The clarity of your chosen swing  

19
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:42,320
points is probably the most important aspect.
The clearer the swing low and high, and the more  

20
00:01:42,320 --> 00:01:48,800
defined the trend between these points, the more 
reliable your Fibonacci levels are likely to be. 
  

21
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:55,560
One common mistake is trying to force Fib 
levels to fit where they don't naturally apply. 

22
00:01:55,560 --> 00:02:02,120
Remember, not every price move will align 
perfectly with Fib levels, and that's okay. 
  

23
00:02:02,120 --> 00:02:06,040
The most helpful Fib retracements 
are those that are obvious on the  

24
00:02:06,040 --> 00:02:12,280
chart without much effort to spot them.
If you find yourself squinting at the chart  

25
00:02:12,280 --> 00:02:19,440
or trying to convince yourself that a level fits, 
it might be best to look for a clearer setup.
 
  

26
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:24,280
When applying Fibonacci retracements, it's 
helpful to think about the market structure. 

27
00:02:24,280 --> 00:02:29,400
In an uptrend, for example, you might 
look for buying opportunities near  

28
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:35,880
these Fib levels, as the price pulls back.
The idea is that the trend will eventually  

29
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:42,960
continue, and these retracement levels offer 
potential entry points, at a better price.
 
  

30
00:02:42,960 --> 00:02:48,360
Number one rule is that Fibonacci 
levels work best in trending markets. 

31
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:55,040
Without a clear trend, these levels lose their 
significance and impact on price movement. 

32
00:02:55,040 --> 00:03:01,360
When you spot a trend, look for the logical price 
swings to place your Fibonacci retracement tool. 

33
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:05,920
This step is critical and often 
where most traders struggle. 

34
00:03:05,920 --> 00:03:11,280
The trick is to find the most relevant high 
and low points that represent the current  

35
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:14,560
market conditions. 
 
So in this uptrend,  

36
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:19,400
I would draw the Fib retracement from 
this swing low, to this swing high. 

37
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:24,800
For this downtrend, I would draw it from 
this swing high, to the swing low. 
  

38
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:29,760
Once you've placed your Fib levels, you'll 
notice several key retracement levels. 

39
00:03:30,440 --> 00:03:37,040
The most commonly used are 
23, 38, 50 and 61% levels. 

40
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:45,240
These lines can act as potential support areas in 
an uptrend, or resistance zones in a downtrend. 

41
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:50,400
Many traders focus primarily 
on the 61% retracement level,  

42
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:55,560
as it's often considered the "golden ratio."
But I wouldn’t discount the power of  

43
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:58,800
other levels. 
 
In strong trends,  

44
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:05,720
price might only retrace to the 38% level 
before continuing in the trend direction. 

45
00:04:05,720 --> 00:04:11,280
In weaker trends, price might 
extend to the 78% level.
 
  

46
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:18,680
Now, it's worth noting that these Fibonacci levels 
don't act as exact support or resistance points. 

47
00:04:18,680 --> 00:04:23,320
Instead, they help you find 
areas where price might react. 

48
00:04:23,320 --> 00:04:28,120
So think of them as zones, 
rather than precise lines. 
  

49
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:33,800
Remember, Fibonacci levels often become 
self-fulfilling prophecies in the market. 

50
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:36,800
Many traders watch these same levels 
and place their orders around them. 

51
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:41,680
This collective action can create 
real support and resistance zones. 
  

52
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:47,960
And please note that Fibonacci levels struggle 
in sideways or ranging conditions. If the  

53
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:52,760
market is consolidating, it's often 
better to wait for a clear breakout  

54
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:59,320
before applying a Fibonacci analysis.
 
 
 
Here’s another common mistake. When you apply  

55
00:04:59,320 --> 00:05:06,560
Fibonacci retracements to very small price moves 
or shorter timeframes, you might run into some  

56
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:14,320
issues that can make your trading less effective.
Think about it this way: on shorter timeframes,  

57
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:18,680
price movements are often more 
erratic and less significant. 

58
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:23,280
These small, rapid price changes 
don't always reflect the true market  

59
00:05:23,280 --> 00:05:27,680
trend or important levels. 
 
When you try to use Fibonacci  

60
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:34,120
retracements on these short-term moves, the 
levels you get are often too close together. 

61
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:41,680
This closeness makes it hard to tell which levels 
are truly important, and which are just noise.
  

62
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:46,320
Another problem with using Fibonacci on 
short timeframes is that you're more likely  

63
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:51,560
to see false breakouts and price spikes.
These quick, sharp moves can trick you  

64
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:56,120
into thinking a level has been 
broken, when it hasn't really. 

65
00:05:56,120 --> 00:06:03,160
This can lead to poor signals, like entering 
a trade too early or exiting one too soon.
  

66
00:06:03,160 --> 00:06:08,760
Think about it: stops and take-profit 
points are key for managing your trades. 

67
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:13,120
But when you use Fib retracements 
on short timeframes, it becomes  

68
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:17,880
tricky to place these effectively.
The retracement levels are so close  

69
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:24,320
together that they create narrow confluences.
This means there's not much room between levels,  

70
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:29,720
making it hard to set stops that protect 
you from normal market noise, while still  

71
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:34,600
giving your trade room to breathe.
 
So, what's the solution? Focus on  

72
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:41,640
larger timeframes when you apply Fib levels.
You get a clearer view of the long-term trend. 

73
00:06:41,640 --> 00:06:45,880
This helps you apply Fibonacci 
retracements in the right direction,  

74
00:06:45,880 --> 00:06:51,840
aligning with the overall market movement.
 
When you use Fibonacci retracements on larger  

75
00:06:51,840 --> 00:06:56,000
timeframes, you're looking at 
more significant price moves. 

76
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,040
These bigger swings are more likely 
to represent important market levels. 

77
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:07,080
The levels drawn on these larger moves are 
spaced further apart, making it easier to  

78
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:12,040
see which levels might be important.
 
And you don't have to stick to just  

79
00:07:12,040 --> 00:07:18,160
one timeframe. You can use a multi-timeframe 
approach. You might start with a larger timeframe  

80
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:25,840
to find the overall trend and major Fibonacci 
levels, then zoom in to a smaller timeframe. 
 
  

81
00:07:25,840 --> 00:07:29,640
Another benefit of placing 
Fibs on larger timeframes,  

82
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:35,000
is that it can help you avoid overtrading.
When you focus on smaller moves, it's  

83
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,960
tempting to take many trades, thinking 
each small retracement is significant. 

84
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:46,280
But by zooming out and looking at the bigger 
picture, you can be more selective with your  

85
00:07:46,280 --> 00:07:52,320
trades, focusing on the moves that 
are more likely to be significant.
 
  

86
00:07:52,320 --> 00:07:59,800
When we talk about retracements, we're looking at 
how much a price pulls back after a strong move.  

87
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:07,120
These pullbacks can be shallow, or deep.
 
Shallow retracements happen in strong trends. When  

88
00:08:07,120 --> 00:08:13,680
a market is moving with conviction, it doesn't 
pull back much before continuing its journey. 

89
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:21,240
In these cases, you'll often see the 
price only retreat to the 23 or 38% areas. 

90
00:08:21,240 --> 00:08:27,360
The trend is so strong that it doesn't need 
much time to refuel, before zooming off again. 

91
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:31,160
When you spot these shallow pullbacks 
it's a sign that the trend is  

92
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:36,560
healthy and likely to continue. 
 
Deep retracements are more common  

93
00:08:36,560 --> 00:08:42,600
when a trend isn't fully established yet.
The price might make several ups and downs,  

94
00:08:42,600 --> 00:08:47,320
testing previous highs or 
lows without breaking them. 

95
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:54,640
Deep retracements often reach the 
61, 78, or even 88 Fib levels. 
  

96
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:59,480
These deeper pullbacks can be tricky.
They might make you think the trend is  

97
00:08:59,480 --> 00:09:04,200
over, but it's not always the case.
It's more like the market is taking  

98
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:10,680
a longer break, perhaps reassessing its 
direction before deciding to continue.
  

99
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:15,960
The key difference between shallow and deep 
retracements, is in what they tell us about  

100
00:09:15,960 --> 00:09:19,440
the strength of the trend.
Shallow retracements  

101
00:09:19,440 --> 00:09:26,360
signal a strong, confident trend.
The market barely hesitates before pushing on. 

102
00:09:26,360 --> 00:09:31,920
Deep retracements suggest more uncertainty. 
The trend might still continue,  

103
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:37,440
but it's taking its time to gather strength.
 
 
If you see a shallow retracement in a strong  

104
00:09:37,440 --> 00:09:43,280
trend, it might be a good opportunity 
to join in the direction of that trend. 

105
00:09:43,280 --> 00:09:48,720
With deep retracements, you might need to 
be more cautious. While they can still lead  

106
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:55,200
to continuation of the trend, there's also a 
higher chance the trend might be losing steam. 

107
00:09:55,200 --> 00:10:03,720
And if the price retraces 100% of the last move, 
it might be a sign that the trend has failed.
  

108
00:10:03,720 --> 00:10:09,360
Now, when price reaches a Fib level, 
look for specific candlestick patterns. 

109
00:10:09,360 --> 00:10:14,360
These patterns can confirm if the 
level is likely to hold, or break. 

110
00:10:14,360 --> 00:10:18,240
It's like getting a second 
opinion before making a trade. 

111
00:10:18,240 --> 00:10:23,600
There are a lot of candlesticks, but the most 
useful patterns at Fib levels are engulfing  

112
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:29,320
patterns, and candles with long wicks. 
 
Candles with a long lower wick  

113
00:10:29,320 --> 00:10:34,400
show up at the end of a down move.
This long wick shows that sellers tried to  

114
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:41,160
push price lower, but buyers stepped in and pushed 
it back up. When you see it at a Fibonacci support  

115
00:10:41,160 --> 00:10:48,200
level, it might mean the down move is over.
 
If you spot a candle with a long upper wicks at  

116
00:10:48,200 --> 00:10:55,280
a Fibonacci resistance level, pay close attention.
They often signal the end of up moves. Buyers  

117
00:10:55,280 --> 00:10:59,520
tried to push price higher, 
but sellers took control. 
  

118
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:06,400
Engulfing patterns are also decent signals. 
In a bullish engulfing pattern, a large green  

119
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:13,880
candle completely covers the previous red candle. 
This shows buyers taking control from sellers. 
  

120
00:11:13,880 --> 00:11:20,000
A bearish engulfing pattern is the opposite, 
with a large red candle covering the previous  

121
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:26,880
green one. These patterns at Fibonacci 
levels can be strong reversal signals.
 

122
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:34,520
From my experience, using candlesticks with 
Fibonacci levels works best on longer timeframes. 

123
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:40,120
This is because bigger moves tend to respect 
Fibonacci levels more. And candlestick patterns  

124
00:11:40,120 --> 00:11:47,560
on longer timeframes often carry more weight.
 
Let's say price is in an uptrend and pulls  

125
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:52,200
back to the 50% Fib level.
This level acts as a potential  

126
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:58,040
support. If you see a candle with a long 
candlestick forming right at this level, it's  

127
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:04,520
a decent sign that the pullback might be over.
The Fib level shows where buyers might step in,  

128
00:12:04,520 --> 00:12:11,760
and the candle shows that they actually did.
 
Here, price is in a downtrend and bounces  

129
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:16,320
up to the 38% Fib level.
This level will act as a  

130
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:21,640
potential resistance in a downtrend.
If an engulfing candle forms here,  

131
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:26,920
it implies the bounce might be over.
So the Fib level shows where sellers  

132
00:12:26,920 --> 00:12:33,120
might return, and the engulfing candle 
shows they're actually taking control.
  

133
00:12:33,120 --> 00:12:36,520
These engulfing patterns at 
Fib levels show a sudden,  

134
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:42,040
strong shift in who's controlling the market.
And an engulfing pattern that completely  

135
00:12:42,040 --> 00:12:48,920
swallows several previous candles at a 
key Fibonacci level is hard to ignore.
  

136
00:12:48,920 --> 00:12:55,320
Volume can add another layer of confirmation 
to candlestick patterns at Fibonacci levels. 

137
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:59,240
A reversal candle with high 
volume at a Fibonacci support  

138
00:12:59,240 --> 00:13:06,920
level is more convincing than one with low volume.
The high volume shows strong buying interest right  

139
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:13,040
where buyers were expected to step in.
 
Now, one common mistake is to focus  

140
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:19,160
only on exact Fibonacci levels.
As I said, in reality, these levels  

141
00:13:19,160 --> 00:13:24,480
are more like zones than exact lines.
A candlestick pattern doesn't have to  

142
00:13:24,480 --> 00:13:31,920
form exactly at a Fibonacci level to be valid.
If it's close, it's worth paying attention to.
  

143
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:35,440
And another key point is to 
look at the bigger picture. 

144
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:42,360
A candlestick pattern at a Fib level is more 
meaningful if it aligns with the larger trend. 

145
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:50,160
For example, a bullish pattern, at a Fibonacci 
support level, in an overall uptrend, is typically  

146
00:13:50,160 --> 00:13:57,120
stronger than one that goes against the trend.
 
The “Golden zone” method is a smart way to  

147
00:13:57,120 --> 00:14:01,760
trade using Fibonacci levels.
This method focuses on the  

148
00:14:01,760 --> 00:14:10,320
50% - 61% area, which we call the Golden Ratio.
First, you find a clear trend in the market. 

149
00:14:10,320 --> 00:14:16,520
You then apply Fibonacci tools to this trend.
You’ve practically market the key levels where  

150
00:14:16,520 --> 00:14:20,400
the price might turn around.
 
The strategy gets interesting  

151
00:14:20,400 --> 00:14:25,920
when the price starts to move against 
the trend, when price starts going up. 

152
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:30,800
You watch closely as it 
moves past the 50% Fib level. 

153
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:36,720
The key is to see if the price can 
break and close above the 61% level. 

154
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:40,280
In the perfect scenario, the 
price reaches the 50 – 61 % zone,  

155
00:14:40,280 --> 00:14:46,920
but doesn’t close above it. And this could be a 
signal that the downtrend is ready to continue.
 
  

156
00:14:46,920 --> 00:14:51,640
In real market, the price will 
touch and even go a bit above  

157
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:59,040
this area. This doesn’t invalidate the setup.
So, it's okay if the price goes above the 61 line.  

158
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:05,160
Once it returns below the 61.8% line, 
that's a good sign for our strategy.
  

159
00:15:05,160 --> 00:15:09,880
This moment is when we get ready to make 
a move. We're looking for signs that the  

160
00:15:09,880 --> 00:15:14,440
price is about to turn back down.
Maybe it's a bearish candle forming,  

161
00:15:14,440 --> 00:15:19,920
or other factors lining up.
The idea is to catch the market just as  

162
00:15:19,920 --> 00:15:27,560
it's deciding to follow the original trend again.
 
In this chart, once we see the price bounce off  

163
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:32,640
the Golden zone, we start looking 
for a move back up. The next target  

164
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:38,520
might be the 38% Fibonacci level.
If the price breaks above the 38%  

165
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:43,640
level, it could mean the previous 
uptrend is picking up steam again. 

166
00:15:43,640 --> 00:15:51,680
After the 38% level, the next stop might be the 
23% level. This is another place where the price  

167
00:15:51,680 --> 00:15:56,280
might pause or bounce a little.
But if the uptrend is strong,  

168
00:15:56,280 --> 00:16:01,560
even this level might not hold.
In that case, we could see the price go all  

169
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:09,080
the way back to where the downward move started.
We call this a 100% retracement.
 
  

170
00:16:09,080 --> 00:16:13,760
So these Fib levels aren't just 
targets for where the price might go. 

171
00:16:13,760 --> 00:16:19,120
They're also useful for managing your trade.
You can use these levels to decide  

172
00:16:19,120 --> 00:16:23,160
when to take some profits.
For instance, you might decide  

173
00:16:23,160 --> 00:16:32,040
to sell a part of your position when the price 
hits the 38% level, and more at the 23% level. 

174
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:35,240
If the price never got 
higher than the Golden zone,  

175
00:16:35,240 --> 00:16:42,400
you might put your stop loss just above that line.
This way, if the market suddenly changes direction  

176
00:16:42,400 --> 00:16:49,160
after you entered, you're protected.
 
 
Combining multiple Fib retracements will  

177
00:16:49,160 --> 00:16:54,480
help you find stronger trade setups.
Start by looking at the big picture. 

178
00:16:54,480 --> 00:17:00,600
Draw Fibonacci retracements on larger 
timeframes, like the daily chart. 

179
00:17:00,600 --> 00:17:04,560
This shows you the main 
trend and important levels. 
  

180
00:17:04,560 --> 00:17:11,160
Then, zoom in to smaller timeframes, like 
1-hour charts, and draw Fibonacci retracements  

181
00:17:11,160 --> 00:17:17,400
there too. After that, you might see some 
levels from the bigger timeframes matching  

182
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:23,080
up with levels on the smaller timeframes. 
These matching levels create confluence. 

183
00:17:23,080 --> 00:17:28,920
For example, the 38% Fibonacci level 
on the daily chart might line up with  

184
00:17:28,920 --> 00:17:34,480
the 50% level on the 1-hour chart. 
 
This overlap becomes a strong area  

185
00:17:34,480 --> 00:17:39,480
to watch. It's like two different 
paths leading to the same place. 

186
00:17:39,480 --> 00:17:46,040
These levels often act like magnets, pulling 
the price back, before the main trend continues. 

187
00:17:46,040 --> 00:17:51,000
It helps to watch how the price acts 
when it hits these Fibonacci levels. 

188
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:58,240
Does it pause? Does it turn around quickly? These 
reactions can tell you how strong the level is. 
 
  

189
00:17:58,240 --> 00:18:03,200
So this technique is all about finding 
areas where different Fibonacci levels  

190
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:09,400
from various timeframes overlap, creating 
a strong support or resistance level. 

191
00:18:09,400 --> 00:18:17,280
In this case, we see a confluence, where the 61% 
Fibonacci retracement from the 4-hour timeframe,  

192
00:18:17,280 --> 00:18:22,080
meets the 38% retracement 
from the daily timeframe. 

193
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:28,760
This overlap creates a buy zone that's much 
stronger than a single Fibonacci level alone.
  

194
00:18:29,960 --> 00:18:36,000
The power of this approach comes from the 
fact that traders using different timeframes  

195
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:42,000
will all see this area as significant.
Those looking at the daily chart will  

196
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:49,960
see the 38% level, while those on the 
4-hour chart will notice the 61% level. 

197
00:18:49,960 --> 00:18:53,360
When both groups see the 
price reacting at this zone,  

198
00:18:53,360 --> 00:18:58,720
it can create a self-fulfilling prophecy, 
increasing the likelihood of a bounce.
  

199
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:04,280
Combining Fibonacci retracements 
this way helps filter out weaker  

200
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:10,360
setups and focuses your attention on 
the most promising trade opportunities. 

201
00:19:10,360 --> 00:19:15,120
It's not just about drawing lines on 
a chart, but about building a complete  

202
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:21,120
picture of potential market turning points.
In this example, the price pulled back to the  

203
00:19:21,120 --> 00:19:28,800
confluence zone and found support there, which 
is exactly what we look for in an uptrend. 
 
  

204
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:35,280
In this chart, we see another example of 
confluence. Two different Fibonacci retracements,  

205
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:40,160
drawn on different timeframes, have 
aligned at the same price area. 

206
00:19:40,160 --> 00:19:46,280
This creates a strong resistance zone, 
setting up a potential selling opportunity. 

207
00:19:46,280 --> 00:19:55,840
In this case, we see a confluence between the 
4-hour 38% level and the 1-hour 50% Fib level. 

208
00:19:55,840 --> 00:20:02,800
This is a key resistance zone where sellers 
might enter the market, in a previous downtrend. 

209
00:20:02,800 --> 00:20:08,880
And indeed, this zone acted as a ceiling 
where price struggled to break through,  

210
00:20:08,880 --> 00:20:13,680
then changed direction.
 
 
Fibonacci and moving averages  

211
00:20:13,680 --> 00:20:18,800
combo is also a viable method.
When used together, they create a  

212
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:24,880
synergy that can confirm your signals.
Fibonacci alone can point to possible  

213
00:20:24,880 --> 00:20:28,640
support or resistance levels, but 
they lack the weight of confirmation. 

214
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:36,720
This is where moving averages step in, adding 
an extra layer of validation to your analysis.
  

215
00:20:36,720 --> 00:20:41,120
Moving averages serve two key 
purposes in this partnership. 

216
00:20:41,120 --> 00:20:47,800
First, they help you spot trends. A simple look at 
the slope of a moving average can tell you if the  

217
00:20:47,800 --> 00:20:53,880
market is trending up, down, or sideways.
And second, moving averages act  

218
00:20:53,880 --> 00:21:00,920
as dynamic support and resistance.
As price moves, these averages shift, creating  

219
00:21:00,920 --> 00:21:07,520
flexible barriers that price often respects.
And when a Fibonacci level lines up with a moving  

220
00:21:07,520 --> 00:21:14,560
average, you've found a spot of confluence. 
 
In this example, price has been climbing  

221
00:21:14,560 --> 00:21:19,560
steadily. You draw your Fibonacci 
retracement from the recent low to the  

222
00:21:19,560 --> 00:21:27,880
high. The 50% retracement level catches your eye.
Now, you notice the 200-period exponential moving  

223
00:21:27,880 --> 00:21:34,880
average is sitting right at that same level.
This is confluence in action. The Fibonacci tool  

224
00:21:34,880 --> 00:21:40,960
and the moving average are both pointing 
to the same price area as significant.
  

225
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:45,720
This confluence increases the odds 
of price reacting at this level. 

226
00:21:45,720 --> 00:21:50,600
You might see price pause, bounce, 
or even reverse at this point. 

227
00:21:50,600 --> 00:21:55,520
It's not a guarantee, but it's 
a strong hint from the market.
  

228
00:21:55,520 --> 00:22:01,480
This combination is powerful because Fib 
retracements can sometimes seem arbitrary. 

229
00:22:01,480 --> 00:22:07,480
And moving averages, on their own, can 
lag behind price action. But together,  

230
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:14,240
they create a more robust analytical framework.
And is not just about finding potential trade  

231
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:22,400
setups. It's also about understanding structure.
These confluence points often mark key levels  

232
00:22:22,400 --> 00:22:29,520
where big players in the market might be active. 
 
It's also worth noting that different traders  

233
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:33,920
might use different Fib levels 
or moving average periods. 

234
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:40,920
Some traders swear by the 61% level, 
combined with the 200-period moving average. 

235
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:45,920
Others might prefer the 50% 
level with the 50-period average. 

236
00:22:45,920 --> 00:22:52,480
The key is to find what works best for your 
trading style, and the markets you trade.
 
  

237
00:22:52,480 --> 00:22:56,880
Now let's talk about how volume 
can confirm Fibonacci levels. 

238
00:22:56,880 --> 00:23:03,160
When price reaches a Fibonacci support area, I 
always look at the volume. Volume is like the  

239
00:23:03,160 --> 00:23:06,240
heartbeat of the market.
When price goes up,  

240
00:23:06,240 --> 00:23:10,800
you often see big spikes in volume.
It's like a lot of people getting  

241
00:23:10,800 --> 00:23:15,480
excited and jumping on board.
But what happens when price pulls  

242
00:23:15,480 --> 00:23:20,360
back to a Fibonacci support level? 
This is where it gets interesting. 

243
00:23:20,360 --> 00:23:24,680
If you see volume getting smaller 
as price pulls back, that's a good  

244
00:23:24,680 --> 00:23:30,320
sign. It means fewer people are selling.
It shows that most people who wanted to  

245
00:23:30,320 --> 00:23:35,480
sell have already done so. There's 
not much selling pressure left.
  

246
00:23:35,480 --> 00:23:41,160
Now, you might think low volume means 
people don't care about the market anymore. 

247
00:23:41,160 --> 00:23:45,040
But that's not true. It just 
means there are fewer sellers. 

248
00:23:45,040 --> 00:23:52,120
Smart buyers see this as a chance to get in 
at a good price, before everyone else notices. 

249
00:23:52,120 --> 00:23:56,480
So watch what happens after price 
bounces off the Fibonacci level. 

250
00:23:56,480 --> 00:23:58,720
If you see a big jump in volume,  

251
00:23:58,720 --> 00:24:04,360
that's a very good sign. It means a lot of 
people are suddenly interested in buying.
  

252
00:24:04,360 --> 00:24:07,880
This high volume after a 
bounce is like a green light. 

253
00:24:07,880 --> 00:24:14,400
It shows that the Fibonacci level worked as 
support, and now more people are jumping in. 

254
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:20,680
It's a sign that the upward move might continue.
 
Using volume with Fibonacci levels  

255
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:25,280
also helps you spot fake-outs.
Sometimes price might dip below  

256
00:24:25,280 --> 00:24:31,400
a Fibonacci level, scaring some traders.
But if volume stays low during this dip,  

257
00:24:31,400 --> 00:24:36,680
it might just be a trick. The 
real move could still be upwards.
  

258
00:24:36,680 --> 00:24:42,080
So when you see price approach a Fibonacci 
level with declining volume, get ready. 

259
00:24:42,080 --> 00:24:48,320
This could be a great entry point. But don't 
jump in just yet. Wait for that volume spike  

260
00:24:48,320 --> 00:24:55,120
after the bounce. That's your confirmation.
 
This method works in downtrends too. If price  

261
00:24:55,120 --> 00:25:00,760
is falling and then hits a Fibonacci 
resistance level, watch the volume. 

262
00:25:00,760 --> 00:25:06,600
If it drops off as price goes up to the 
level, sellers might be running out of steam. 

263
00:25:06,600 --> 00:25:14,560
A big volume spike downwards, after touching 
the level, could signal more downside to come.
 
  

264
00:25:14,560 --> 00:25:20,480
One of the most underrated ways to trade 
Fibonacci levels involves divergences. 

265
00:25:20,480 --> 00:25:27,320
A divergence is a leading trading signal, and it 
can help confirm if a price reaction is likely. 

266
00:25:27,320 --> 00:25:34,640
It’s simple, just choose a momentum indicator. I 
prefer to use the MACD. This indicator shows if  

267
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:41,960
a trend is strong or weak. Yes, it lags, but 
we don’t need crossovers or other signals. 
  

268
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:46,720
We simply look at inefficiencies 
between the price and the oscillator. 

269
00:25:46,720 --> 00:25:52,040
When MACD don't match what price 
is doing, it's called divergence. 

270
00:25:52,040 --> 00:25:58,240
And as I said, a divergence at a Fibonacci 
level is a strong sign of a possible reversal.
  

271
00:25:58,960 --> 00:26:04,760
Let's talk about how this works in a downtrend.
Imagine price hits the 50% Fib  

272
00:26:04,760 --> 00:26:10,000
level and starts to reverse.
Then you look at your oscillator. If  

273
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:16,960
price is making higher highs, but your indicator 
is making lower highs, that's a divergence. 

274
00:26:16,960 --> 00:26:22,800
It means the upward momentum is slowing, 
even though price is still trying to move up. 

275
00:26:22,800 --> 00:26:28,440
This implies the bounce might be over, 
and the downtrend could resume. 
  

276
00:26:28,440 --> 00:26:33,520
The same idea works in uptrends too.
Let's say price is rising and then  

277
00:26:33,520 --> 00:26:40,000
pulls back to the 61% Fibonacci level. If 
you see a divergence on your oscillator  

278
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:47,520
right at this level, it's a strong buy signal.
These signals are called leading indicators.  

279
00:26:47,520 --> 00:26:52,320
They hint at what might happen before 
price actually turns. That's why they're  

280
00:26:52,320 --> 00:26:58,280
so valuable. They give you a heads up, 
letting you prepare for a potential trade.
  

281
00:26:58,280 --> 00:27:03,640
Of course, a divergence at Fibonacci 
levels doesn't guarantee a reversal.  

282
00:27:03,640 --> 00:27:07,960
It just makes one more likely.
You could look for the other signals  

283
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:15,320
we’ve discussed, like candlestick patterns 
or volume changes, to confirm the signal.
 
 
 
 

284
00:27:15,320 --> 00:27:19,280
Probably my favorite strategy is 
to look for confluences between  

285
00:27:19,280 --> 00:27:25,880
the FIB levels and supply or demand areas.
It doesn't happen often, but when it does,  

286
00:27:25,880 --> 00:27:31,800
it can be a sign of something special.
 
In this example, notice that the price  

287
00:27:31,800 --> 00:27:36,960
is approaching a key demand area 
that lines up with a FIB level. 

288
00:27:36,960 --> 00:27:42,240
That's a confluence perfect for a trade.
If the price bounces off that area,  

289
00:27:42,240 --> 00:27:47,080
it could be the start of a beautiful 
uptrend that you can ride.
  

290
00:27:47,080 --> 00:27:52,520
On the flip side, if you see the price 
approaching a major supply area, and that  

291
00:27:52,520 --> 00:27:59,040
coincides with a Fib level, it could be a sign 
that the buyers are about to run out of steam. 

292
00:27:59,040 --> 00:28:03,200
If the price gets rejected at that 
level, it might be time to start  

293
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:08,920
hunting for short opportunities.
 
Let's talk about demand areas first. 

294
00:28:08,920 --> 00:28:15,160
These are places where lots of people want to buy.
When the price gets near a demand area,  

295
00:28:15,160 --> 00:28:20,160
and it's also close to a Fibonacci 
level, it's extra special. 

296
00:28:20,160 --> 00:28:24,160
This tells us that the price 
might start going up soon.
  

297
00:28:24,160 --> 00:28:30,320
Think about it like this: You're looking at 
an uptrend. Then the price is going down. 

298
00:28:30,320 --> 00:28:34,400
But then you notice it's 
getting close to a demand area. 

299
00:28:34,400 --> 00:28:42,360
The price is also near a key Fibonacci level.
You may want to monitor closely this area. 
  

300
00:28:42,360 --> 00:28:46,680
Supply areas are spots where 
lots of people want to sell. 

301
00:28:46,680 --> 00:28:52,200
When the price climbs up to a supply 
area, and it matches a Fibonacci level,  

302
00:28:52,200 --> 00:28:59,720
it's another special moment. This might mean the 
price is about to turn around and start falling.
  

303
00:28:59,720 --> 00:29:03,520
Picture this: the market 
is in a general downtrend,  

304
00:29:03,520 --> 00:29:09,680
then the price has been climbing for a while.
Then you see it's approaching a supply area. 

305
00:29:09,680 --> 00:29:13,760
The price is also near an 
important Fibonacci level. 

306
00:29:13,760 --> 00:29:19,680
This is when you start thinking the 
upward move might be running out of steam. 

307
00:29:19,680 --> 00:29:25,280
These confluences are like secret messages in 
the market. They don't happen all the time,  

308
00:29:25,280 --> 00:29:30,040
but when they do, you pay attention. 
 
Again, here price bounce off a demand  

309
00:29:30,040 --> 00:29:35,000
area that lines up with a Fibonacci 
level. This is a good time to enter a  

310
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:40,480
buy position and ride the price up 
as it starts a new upward move. 
  

311
00:29:40,480 --> 00:29:45,880
And here, price hit a supply area 
that matches a Fibonacci level,  

312
00:29:45,880 --> 00:29:53,320
and then start to fall. This was a good time 
to sell, as price started a new downward move. 

313
00:29:53,320 --> 00:30:07,440
Now, if you’re ready for more interesting trading 
guides, go ahead and watch one of these videos.

